sentences: Albertine Morin-Labrecque (sometimes Labrecque-Morin) (8 June 1886 – 22 or 25 September 1957) was a Canadian pianist, soprano, composer, and music educator.
A square and a street in Montreal were named after her in 1984.
She pursued further studies in piano privately with Romain-Octave Pelletier I for a number of years.
In 1901 Morin-Labrecque began giving regular recitals.
During the first two decades of the century she regularly gave recital tours in both Canada and the United States, and actively studied harmony and music composition.

sentences: In 1922 Morin-Labrecque established the chamber ensemble Trio de Montréal with her sister, violinist Jeanne Labrecque, and cellist Yvette Lamontagne.
section: == Studies in Paris and later career ==

sentences: From 1922–1951 she served on the faculty of the Université de Montréal (UM) where she taught music analysis, pedagogy, piano and voice.
section: == Studies in Paris and later career ==

sentences: She was awarded an honorary doctorate from the UM in 1935.
